Inner join, and on versus using.

An inner join keeps only the rows that have a match on both sides. The word inner is optional; a bare join means the same thing, but writing inner join reads better in real code.

There are two ways to specify the predicate. The on clause takes any boolean expression and is fully general: it allows inequalities, like joining on a date falling between a start and an end, and multi-column predicates. The using clause is shorthand for when the join columns have the same name on both sides; it produces a single column in the output instead of two.

One thing to avoid: natural join, which auto-joins on every same-named column. It looks clever, and it breaks badly the moment somebody adds a new column with a colliding name.
